ingly more important. Material things, as in the \"manufacturing\" are less and less important. i do not mean this necessarily in a bad way. but what happens when what is more valuable in the world is completely un-intangible. this happens in the journalism industry for example. what these newspapers sold was a newspaper, a collection of ink and paper. this is not the case anymore. if newspapers can\'t sell their newspaper, what will they sell? what will they sell if they can have the equivalent for free? is the difference between paid content and free content just a difference of quality? i don\'t think so. for me, all this comes down to the problem of capitalism. we live in a world that depends on being able to get money out of everything, but i don\'t think this doesn\'t work anymore. not everyone can have a job anymore. not everything worthwhile doing is cost-effective anymore.','1-4-2012','','publish','open','open','','12-4-2011','','','2012-01-08 18:53:10','2012-01-08 18:53:10','',0,'http://vrasen.com/xyz/?p=27',0,'post','',0),(14,1,'2011-12-27 19:16:30','2011-12-27 19:16:30','I like cities. I like space. I\'m definitely more space-oriented than time oriented. I like how every city is similar but the different. Not how they are different despite being similar, but similar and different at the same time. I like how they join and separate people, how you can be anyone you would like to be. I find it interesting how it is so anonymous, yet so public. I always think about the people who live in a city and how the place where you live influences who you are, what you think, what you do. I believe that being \'who you want to be\' (whatever that means) is a lot more about choosing where you live and who you spend time with than anything else. Your surroundings are who you are and it is by choosing your surrounding that you get to choose who you are, rather than the typical assumption that there is some direct relationship between who you wish to be and who you can be. While I took a bit of a detour there, i think that\'s one of my obsessions with the city: how the make you who you are in a much more deeper way than any other human setting.','12-27-11','','publish','open','open','','12-27-11','','','2011-12-27 19:16:30','2011-12-27 19:16:30','',0,'http://vrasen.com/xyz/?p=14',0,'post','',0),(15,1,'2011-12-27 19:15:43','2011-12-27 19:15:43','I like cities. I like space. I\'m definitely more space-oriented than time oriented. I like how every city is similar but the different. Not how they are different despite being similar, but similar and different at the same time. I like how they join and separate people, how you can be anyone you would like to be. I find it interesting how it is so anonymous, yet so public. I always think about the people who live in a city and how the place where you live influences who you are, what you think, what you do. I believe that being \'who you want to be\' (whatever that means) is a lot more about choosing where you live and who you spend time with than anything else. Your surroundings are who you are and it is by choosing your surrounding that you get to choose who you are, rather than the typical assumption that there is some direct relationship between who you wish to be and who you can be. While I took a bit of a detour there, i think that\'s one of my','12-27-11','','inherit','open','open','','14-revision','','','2011-12-27 19:15:43','2011-12-27 19:15:43','',14,'http://vrasen.com/xyz/?p=15',0,'revision','',0),(16,1,'2011-12-27 02:45:30','2011-12-27 02:45:30','what\'s the point of it all? you work so hard for so many things but at the end, does it really matter? we get so stressed out about life, we take it so seriously, but really, it doesn\'t make any differences. if you\'re successful or a failure, if you\'re poor or you\'re rich, if you\'re alone or accompanied. at the end, it\'s all the same. this is not a message of \"go do what you want, forget about what the world thinks\" [that\'s a