er a lot about. we, as human individuals, are many times unable to see in the macro terms of history. how do i fit into these time lapses? should be thinking of it in this way, or just go about my day as the worker ant in the colony? the life of the colony is always a lot longer and more monumental than the life of the worker ant? is it human nature to ignore the macro time frame imposed by the the institution of time upon us? i don not wish to ignore these. i would like to live my life thinking and considering how i fit into the  mighty potent time. It is of course, easier to ignore this fact. It is a pretty big headache to acknowledge your lack of importance in the macro view of the world. I think no single individual has single handedly shaped the world and change the course of the river of time.   Quite frankly, i\'m not very sure.','1-2-2011','','inherit','open','open','','24-revision-2','','','2012-01-02 20:05:55','2012-01-02 20:05:55','',24,'http://vrasen.com/xyz/?p=38',0,'revision','',0),(39,1,'2012-01-01 18:19:10','2012-01-01 18:19:10','It\'s not that you want to be with \'someone\' to not be alone. The part that\'s sociaially made up is not only the one about that special someone. It\'s also the part about the social human being. What really happens to that lonely person? How much of the human being is actually capable of being alone, and how much of it is socially constructed. Well, i guess that at then end there isn\'t so much of a difference... But i wonder, how much happier would we be without this need for other people (especially for the people who don\'t have anyone)? I wonder that for myself. Maybe i should just forget about it all, and try to get rid of that, but at the same time i do think \"Happiness is real only when shared\". Is it? How should we share it? with whom? is happiness real only when shared with the same person?','1-1-2011','','inherit','open','open','','21-revision-2','','','2012-01-01 18:19:10','2012-01-01 18:19:10','',21,'http://vrasen.com/xyz/?p=39',0,'revision','',0),(41,1,'2012-01-11 00:34:53','2012-01-11 00:34:53','Recently, i\'ve thought a lot about what kinda of life do i want for myself. I think i really don\'t want the suburban, soccer mon, minivan, cable TV watching, conservative kind of life. That\'s ok in itself, but I don\'t think that\'s for me. I don\'t want the opposite either which is maybe the life of the artist, struggling from day to day, spending more time in \"hanging out\"  than anything else... I want to live comfortably, i like to work (even do work/life balance should be important). I don\'t need a lot of people in my life, maybe I don\'t need a lot of people in my life. But I wouldn\'t like a life with a lot of responsibilities (kids, mortgage, credit card debt). I would like a life with a lot of change. I would like to live in a lot of different places in the world. I don\'t want to grow old. I want to walk to work. I want to live in the city. I would like to live in a place where things are actually happening. I would like to go out to dinner from time to time. I would like to tap dance my way to work, not because i get paid to much, but because i spend the right amount of time working in something that is interesting and exciting. I want to have a life of learning. I like learning. I like doing different things. I get tired quite easily and quickly of things. I can adapt to change pretty quickly. I want to meet people and have friends. I don\'t need it, but i like to be around people more than i like maintaining relationships. I don\'t need to be rich, but I would like to cause a change in whatever i\'m doing, even if it\'s minimal. I want to be great at whatever I do. I want to have a simple and fulfilling life, without the pressures of society hanging on over me, being creative, trying out new things and','1-10-2011','','inherit','open','open','','40-revision','','','2012-01-11 00:34:53','2012-01-11 00:34:53','',40,'http://vrasen.com/xyz/?p=41',0,'revision','',0),(43,1,'2012-01-22 14:46:00','2012-01-22 14:46:00','It\'s been a while, hasn\'t it.\r\n\r\nRecently, I\'ve been thinking about hard work. I consider myself a hard worker. Maybe not the hardest, but one nonetheless. I\'ve always thought, does any of this make any difference? Do the best things in life go to the hardest working people? The other question would be: Am i doing this in order to complete a goal or am I doing this for itself? unfortunately, I think the latter. I think things this way in order to receive a payout at the end, to see the reward of my work. There is also an issue of pride that comes along with it. I pride myself in being a hard worker and it has, surprisingly, become part of my ethos. I define myself through this attitude and sometimes I don\'t know how to do things any other way. I\'ve met people that seem to be successful and don\'t seem to have this preocupation that I have. I know that I should learn at least a little of how to do things this other way, but in the meantime, I am happy things the way i\'m used to.','1-22-2012','','publish','open','open','','1-22-2012','','','2012-01-22 14:46:00','2012-01-22 14:46:00','',0,'http://vrasen.com/xyz/?p=43',0,'post','',0),(44,1,'2012-01-22 14:43:08','2012-01-22 14:43:08','It\'s been a while, hasn\'t it.\n\nRecently, I\'ve been thinking about hard work. I consider myself a hard worker. Maybe not the hardest, but one nonetheless. I\'ve always thought, does any of this make any difference? Do the best things in life go to the hardest working people? The other question would be: Am i doing this in order to complete a goal or am I doing this for itself? unfortunately, I think the latter. I think things this way in order to receive a payout at the end, to see the reward of my work. There is also an issue of pride that comes along with it. I pride myself in being a hard worker and it has, surprisingly, become part of my ethos. I define myself through this attitude and sometimes I don\'t know how to d